data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code has three patterns that don't exist in ASP.NET Core:

| .NET Framework Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Internally called `Thread.Abort` — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Just return from the action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` called `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code — ASP.NET Core (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Web Forms event handler → MVC action returning IActionResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Response.Clear / Response.Write / Response.End → return FileContentResult
        // ASP.NET Core handles Content-Disposition and streaming for you.
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect("/login", true) → return RedirectResult
            // No Thread.Abort, no endResponse parameter.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch block is removed entirely —
        // it is never thrown in .NET 6+.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Response.End()` → just return**
In Web Forms, `Response.End()` called `Thread.Abort` to stop pipeline execution. In ASP.NET Core, returning an `IActionResult` ends the response naturally — no abort needed.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (`endResponse`) parameter triggered `Thread.Abort` to prevent code after the redirect from executing. In MVC/Core, `return Redirect(...)` exits the action method via normal control flow — the same guarantee, without the abort.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed**
This catch existed solely because `Response.Redirect(..., true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect. Since `Redirect()` returns normally, no exception is thrown — the catch block is dead code.

**4. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` → null-safe access**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` for unauthenticated requests. Added `?.` and `?? true` to handle this safely.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Leaving `Response.End()` calls** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime — no compile error |
| **Catching `ThreadAbortException`** | Never thrown in .NET 8; the catch block is dead code that obscures real bugs |
| **Using `Response.Redirect()` without returning** | Code after the redirect *will execute* in ASP.NET Core (no abort to stop it). Always `return Redirect(...)` |
| **Not null-checking `User.Identity`** | `NullReferenceException` for anonymous requests in Core |
| **Writing directly to `Response.Body`** | If you must stream (large files), use `return File(stream, ...)` or write to `Response.Body` then `return new EmptyResult()` — never call `Response.End()` |

## If You Have Long-Running Request Work

For actions that do expensive processing, accept `CancellationToken` to honor client disconnects (replaces the old `Response.IsClientConnected` check):

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically wires this to HttpContext.RequestAborted
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This is the cooperative cancellation model that replaces the old `Thread.Abort`-based pipeline termination.
